column3: Correct the module missing check in the ModuleManagerCore
column4: In the current status, the ModuleManager still reported the `CycleDependencyException` in the `module-missing` case. This PR fixes this issue.  Now, the core reports error accurately. 1. Cycle dependency ``` org.apache.skywalking.oap.server.library.module.CycleDependencyException: Exist cycle module dependencies in  BaseB[provider=org.apache.skywalking.oap.server.library.module.ModuleB3Provider] BaseA[provider=org.apache.skywalking.oap.server.library.module.ModuleA2Provider] ```  2. ModuleNotFound ``` org.apache.skywalking.oap.server.library.module.ModuleNotFoundException: dummy module is required by BaseB.P-B2, but not found. ```

column3: Separate config initialization in the plugin out of core level Config.
column4: In the current agent core, the `Config` in the core is heavily binding with many plugins, because it is the only way to do configurations injection through agent.config, properties,  and system env. With the increment of plugins, especially the transport plugin(Kafka) and backend service discovery plugin(k8s), the Config class is being out of control. In this PR, I support all plugins to provide its one or more Config Initialization Services and could initial the plugin configurations used by themselves only. This should be the better way to provide a plugin as an independent module as we mentioned in our design principle. By leveraging our ClassLoader, once the `org.apache.skywalking.apm.agent.core.boot.PluginConfig` implementations loaded, it would be initialized inside the agent core. At the same time, all plugin configurations should be kept unchanged. Users wouldn't feel this change happened.  Resolves #5130 FYI @EvanLjp

column3: Support metrics APIs for agent plugin
column4: In the 8.1.0, we have supported our own toolkit library and MicroMeter integration for metrics in the java application. Now, ShardingSphere community is requesting to collect metrics in the agent plugin system.  Right now, the `transform` and `adapter` systems are for toolkit with activation. In the agent core, we need this kind of simple APIs, such as `MeterFactory#createCounter`, for use inside the agent.

column3: Restore and enhance the endpoint dependency page
column4: In the 8.0.0, we removed the useless endpoint dependency in the main dashboard. Mostly because it is not powerful and very useful.   I think we should add it back as a separate page, like topology. We could name it as `endpoint dependency`.  In this new page, user could select the endpoint and the depth(including upstream and downstream), then the UI could do multiple queries to the upstream and downstream side, rend the dependency based on the traffic(CPM). Also, like the instance dependency, users could click the link between endpoints, and see more metrics.

column3: Query happens when these is no available services/database
column4: In entity, the scope should match the condition, right now, even no service(dashboard or database), the query still happens, but serviceName as NULL. UI should not do this query.  ``` input Entity {     # 1. scope=All, no name is required.     # 2. scope=Service, ServiceInstance and Endpoint, set neccessary serviceName/serviceInstanceName/endpointName     # 3. Scope=ServiceRelation, ServiceInstanceRelation and EndpointRelation     #    serviceName/serviceInstanceName/endpointName is/are the source(s)     #    destServiceName/destServiceInstanceName/destEndpointName is/are destination(s)     #    set necessary names of sources and destinations.     scope: Scope!     serviceName: String     # Normal service is the service having installed agent or metrics reported directly.     # Unnormal service is conjectural service, usually detected by the agent.     normal: Boolean     serviceInstanceName: String     endpointName: String     destServiceName: String     # Normal service is the service having installed agent or metrics reported directly.     # Unnormal service is conjectural service, usually detected by the agent.     destNormal: Boolean     destServiceInstanceName: String     destEndpointName: String } ```

column3: Set up restrict length rules for service, instance and endpoint
column4: In 8.x, as we are using encoding rather than register, the length of service/instance/endpoint are more sensitive to the backend.(We used to only be sensitive in MySQL/H2 storage).  I provide the following config in the core module, and provide default settings too. ```yaml core:   selector: ${SW_CORE:default}   default:     # The max length of service + instance names should be less than 200     serviceNameMaxLength: ${SW_SERVICE_NAME_MAX_LENGTH:70}     instanceNameMaxLength: ${SW_INSTANCE_NAME_MAX_LENGTH:70}     # The max length of service + endpoint names should be less than 240     endpointNameMaxLength: ${SW_ENDPOINT_NAME_MAX_LENGTH:150} ```  Currently, I would not shut down the OAP in the bootstrap process, if users really set the length out of the suggestion values.

column3: Use explicit charset instead of default charset
column4: Implicit use of the platform default charset, which can result in differing behaviour between JVM executions or incorrect behavior if the encoding of the data source doesn't match expectations.

column3: New metrics query protocol v2
column4: Hi dev community  I provide supporting to v2 protocol, which lead to 1. A better dashboard with more powerful configurable capability. @Fine0830 is working on that. 1. Support receiving metrics from 3rd parties, prometheus, zabbix, etc. I and @hanahmily will continue on this.  This PR includes the supports of v2 implementation, and previous v1 supports are still there, but only compatible with previous CLI and UI. Just remove all `numOfxxx` queries supports.  This is the new query protocol ```graphql # Licensed to the Apache Software Foundation (ASF) under one # or more contributor license agreements.  See the NOTICE file # distributed with this work for additional information # regarding copyright ownership.  The ASF licenses this file # to you under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the # "License"); you may not use this file except in compliance # with the License.  You may obtain a copy of the License at # #     http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0 # # Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software # distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS, # WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied. # See the License for the specific language governing permissions and # limitations under the License.  # Metrics v2 query protocol is an alternative metrics query(s) of original v1, # defined in the metric.graphql, top-n-records.graphqls, and aggregation.graphqls. # By leveraging the new ID rule(no register) in the v8, we could query metrics based on name(s) directly.  # Metrics type is a new concept since v8. enum MetricsType {     # Can't find the metrics type definition.     UNKNOWN     # Regular value type is suitable for readMetricsValue, readMetricsValues and sortMetrics     REGULAR_VALUE     # Metrics value includes multiple labels, is suitable for readLabeledMetricsValues     # Label should be assigned before the query happens, such as at the setting stage     LABELED_VALUE     # Heatmap value suitable for readHeatMap     HEATMAP     # Top metrics is for readSampledRecords only.     SAMPLED_RECORD }  input Entity {     # 1. scope=All, no name is required.     # 2. scope=Service, ServiceInstance and Endpoint, set neccessary serviceName/serviceInstanceName/endpointName     # 3. Scope=ServiceRelation, ServiceInstanceRelation and EndpointRelation     #    serviceName/serviceInstanceName/endpointName is/are the source(s)     #    destServiceName/destServiceInstanceName/destEndpointName is/are destination(s)     #    set necessary names of sources and destinations.     scope: Scope!     serviceName: String     # Normal service is the service having installed agent or metrics reported directly.     # Unnormal service is conjectural service, usually detected by the agent.     isNormal: Boolean     serviceInstanceName: String     endpointName: String     destServiceName: String     # Normal service is the service having installed agent or metrics reported directly.     # Unnormal service is conjectural service, usually detected by the agent.     destIsNormal: Boolean     destServiceInstanceName: String     destEndpointName: String }  input MetricsCondition {     # Metrics name, which should be defined in OAL script     # Such as:     # Endpoint_avg = from(Endpoint.latency).avg()     # Then, `Endpoint_avg`     name: String!     # Follow entity definition description.     entity: Entity }  input TopNCondition {     # Metrics name     name: String!     # Could be null if query the global top N.     parentService: String     # Normal service is the service having installed agent or metrics reported directly.     # Unnormal service is conjectural service, usually detected by the agent.     isNormal: Boolean     # Indicate the metrics entity scope.     # This is required in sortMetrics query.     # Only accept scope = Service/ServiceInstance/Endpoint, ignore others due to those are pointless.     scope: Scope     topN: Int!     order: Order! }  type MetricsValues {     # Could be null if no label assigned in the query condition     label: String     # Values of this label value.     values: IntValues }  type HeatMap {     # Each element of values matches the time point of the query duration.     # The element in the IntValues represents the value of the same index bucket     values: [HeatMapColumn!]!     # Bucket describes the ranges of #values represent.     buckets: [Bucket!]! }  type HeatMapColumn {     id: ID!     values: [Long!]! }  # Bucket represents the value range. type Bucket {     # Usually the number represents the min value of this bucket,     # could be `infinite-` string as unbounded value     min: String!     # Usually the number represents the max value of this bucket,     # could be `infinite+` string as unbounded value     max: String! }  type SelectedRecord {     # Literal string name for visualization     name: String!     # ID represents the owner of this entity.     id: ID!     # Usually an integer value as this is metrics.     value: String     # Have value, Only if the record has related trace id.     # UI should show this as an attached value.     refId: ID }  extend type Query {     # Metrics definition metadata query. Response the metrics type which determines the suitable query methods.     typeOfMetrics(name: String!): MetricsType!      # Read metrics single value in the duration of required metrics     readMetricsValue(condition: MetricsCondition!, duration: Duration!): Int!     # Read time-series values in the duration of required metrics     readMetricsValues(condition: MetricsCondition!, duration: Duration!): MetricsValues!     # Read entity list of required metrics and parent entity type.     sortMetrics(condition: TopNCondition!, duration: Duration!): [SelectedRecord!]!     # Read value in the given time duration, usually as a linear.     # labels: the labels you need to query.     readLabeledMetricsValues(condition: MetricsCondition!, labels: [String!]!, duration: Duration!): [MetricsValues!]!     # Heatmap is bucket based value statistic result.     readHeatMap(condition: MetricsCondition!, duration: Duration!): HeatMap     # Read the sampled records     # TopNCondition#scope is not required.     readSampledRecords(condition: TopNCondition!, duration: Duration!): [SelectedRecord!]! } ```  Also, I update the UI submodule in this PR.

column3: Provide Meter(metrics) system
column4: Hi dev  This pull request introduces the meter system into the SkyWalking core. Meter system is compatible with any metrics system in theory. It shares the same streaming calculation core and still pluggable to different protocols and different metrics read modes(pull/push, grpc/http/mq).  Here are the basic and simple usages of the MeterSystem APIs.  ## Meter Creation New meter could be created based on metrics name, function, scope and data type.  1. Metrics name is still the storage entity name. 1. Functions are every similar with the OAL function, just accepting different input. ```java final MeterSystem meterSystem = MeterSystem.meterSystem(getManager()); meterSystem.create("test_long_metrics", "avg", ScopeType.SERVICE, Long.class); ``` NOTICE, this creation should only be called in the `module#prepare` stage, otherwise, `Can't create new metrics anymore` exception will be raised after the **CORE** module `start` stage finished. You may find out, there is a chance `create` could be executed successfully in your own `module#start` stage, but it it just because of the sequence of provider loaded by the class loader, **no guarantee, so please don't do that**.  ## Runtime Calculation `AcceptableValue` is the object created at the runtime to accept new metrics value. ```java          final MeterSystem service = getManager().find(CoreModule.NAME).provider().getService(MeterSystem.class);         Executors.newSingleThreadScheduledExecutor().scheduleAtFixedRate(new Runnable() {             @Override             public void run() {                 final AcceptableValue value = service.buildMetrics("test_long_metrics", Long.class);                 value.accept(MeterEntity.newService("abc"), 5L);                 value.setTimeBucket(TimeBucket.getMinuteTimeBucket(System.currentTimeMillis()));                 service.doStreamingCalculation(value);             }         }, 2, 2, TimeUnit.SECONDS); ```  ## Meter Functions Right now, only `avg` function has been implemented. I submit this PR as soon as possible to get your feedback. I will add more functions.

column3: Metrics about latency of consuming queue
column4: Hi @apache/skywalking-committers and @EvanLjp  I created this issue to track the discussion originally started here, https://github.com/apache/skywalking/issues/5584#issuecomment-700793580. The question of #5584  actually is asking for metrics of MQ consuming latency.  Here it is my proposal  The only high-performance way is to propagate the sending time(header injecting timestamp) in the extension header, https://github.com/apache/skywalking/blob/master/docs/en/protocols/Skywalking-Cross-Process-Propagation-Headers-Protocol-v3.md#extension-header-item.  If you are going to implement this, we should consider making it optional, such as - `sw8-x` = `0-mq_send_timestamp` or `-mq_send_timestamp` - `sw8-x` = `0`  Then, if when the upstream receiving this header, it could be readable by the entry span, the plugin could calculate the latency of this message, add as a new tag as `mq.consum_latency`. Then the OAP could do statistics with a new source.  NOTE, this new field of extension header should be readonly, but wouldn't propagate it because once it is read from the header, it means this message has been consumed.

column3: Fix NPE in shardingjdbc 1.5.4.1
Try to set up cancel-workflow-runs plugin to our Action flows.
column4: Following the talks with the Airflow team here, https://github.com/apache/airflow/issues/11114, Jarek built the very cool plugin to cancel unnecessary tasks.  https://github.com/marketplace/actions/cancel-workflow-runs  @kezhenxu94 Please try to set this up. If you face some issues, we could ping `potiuk`(GitHub id) for help.

column3: Provide server-side meter system
column4: Follow the [mail list discussion](https://lists.apache.org/thread.html/r428cf4727773414be80f26640110b9a089c9defd44c31f3de5ded86f%40%3Cdev.skywalking.apache.org%3E) and [design doc](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1oM0NUvN8cyEzDyHyL5FjSA_hPEhnpxGA782jDWtEgDU/edit#), I'm ready to develop the server-side meter system.   Basically, I will create a new PR to collect the meter from the agent, create a new file to configure the meters and collect it to the backend.

column3: Provide client-side meter system
column4: Follow the [mail list discussion](https://lists.apache.org/thread.html/r428cf4727773414be80f26640110b9a089c9defd44c31f3de5ded86f%40%3Cdev.skywalking.apache.org%3E) and [design doc](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1oM0NUvN8cyEzDyHyL5FjSA_hPEhnpxGA782jDWtEgDU/edit#), I'm ready to develop the client-side meter system.   I will follow these steps to develop, If anyone wants to join me, please let me know:   1. gRPC protocol define. 1. client-side toolkit API and implements. 1. micro-meter framework adapts. 1. backend develops, collects metrics, and save to meter system.

column3: [CVE] Update Jetty version to fix its CVEs
column4: Follow reports from users, old jetty versions have the following  Security Vulnerabilities. Update version to fix these.  https://www.cvedetails.com/vulnerability-list/vendor_id-10410/product_id-34824/Eclipse-Jetty.html

column3: Introduce label system to histogram
column4: Fix #5340   As below image shows that there are three groups and each one contains two percentile, 95%, and 99% ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1960537/91872084-0cb4ea80-ecaa-11ea-830e-2c9a53e1f7fd.png)  In this PR, the bucket unit of the histogram can be set through the metric rule. Since Prometheus official documents confirm the unit of a bucket should be Seconds, but other libraries, for example, open census, can set a different unit.

column3: OAP server failed when use es as storage
column4: First time, I started my skywalking without change of storage config, it succeed. But when I use the elasticsearch as storage, I got an error like this:  org.apache.skywalking.oap.server.starter.OAPServerBootstrap - 59 [main] ERROR [] - org.elasticsearch.client.RestHighLevelClient.ping([Lorg/apache/http/Header;)Z java.lang.NoSuchMethodError: org.elasticsearch.client.RestHighLevelClient.ping([Lorg/apache/http/Header;)Z         at org.apache.skywalking.oap.server.library.client.elasticsearch.ElasticSearchClient.connect(ElasticSearchClient.java:121) ~[library-client-6.6.0.jar:6.6.0]         at org.apache.skywalking.oap.server.storage.plugin.elasticsearch.StorageModuleElasticsearchProvider.start(StorageModuleElasticsearchProvider.java:133) ~[storage-elasticsearch-plugin-6.6.0.jar:6.6.0]         at org.apache.skywalking.oap.server.library.module.BootstrapFlow.start(BootstrapFlow.java:61) ~[library-module-6.6.0.jar:6.6.0]         at org.apache.skywalking.oap.server.library.module.ModuleManager.init(ModuleManager.java:67) ~[library-module-6.6.0.jar:6.6.0]         at org.apache.skywalking.oap.server.starter.OAPServerBootstrap.start(OAPServerBootstrap.java:47) [server-bootstrap-6.6.0.jar:6.6.0]         at org.apache.skywalking.oap.server.starter.OAPServerStartUp.main(OAPServerStartUp.java:28) [server-starter-es7-6.6.0.jar:6.6.0]  My skywalking version is : 6.6.0 elasticsearch version is : 6.5.4 And elasticsearch running successful, but skywalking oap-server failed, whar reason cause this error?

column3: [Significant BUG]Spring Annotation Plugins Makes FULLGC Without Stop
column4: Environment:  19 agents  1 skywalking-oap-service-6.6.0  1 es-6.6.2.  sw-oap-jvm-param: jvm-param -Xmx12g，-Xms12g，-Xmn6，-XX:SurvivorRatio=8  Desc: 19 agents with optional-spring-plugins - spring-annotional-plugins. When the skywalking-opa-servic begins running,this will happen： the jvm-Eden increasing，this will lead to the jvm-OLD increases.When the jvm-OLD is used by 100%,the process will try fgc for all the time,and will provide no service for agent and ui. At this time,the skywalking-opa-service process is exit,but there is no service provided.  I have found,that when the operateID is null,sw will try save the objs into buffer-file.But when the flows become upper and upper,the excessive objs should be given up.  It bothers me a lot,and  I need help

column3: The NoneStreamEsDAO implementation doesn't use real index name to insert
column4: @sunrongxin7666 I have found out the reason of your reported issue. The existing codes are using the template name rather than the index name(with time bucket suffix) to insert data, which is not supported by the ElasticSearch. We haven't a chance to test this case before, thanks for your detailed report, which makes me easier to catch the reason.  All existing metrics and traces insert/update are doing in the right now, but due to profile is new in the 7.0, it seems @mrproliu missed this, and this can't be caught by the current TTL e2e.  Resolves #4794.

column3: Fix sampling and Kafka reporter conflicting.
column4: @peng-yongsheng reported this conflict. As they used to extend the same core service, when both of them are active, which could happen, they can't work together.  But, from the design perspective, I notice, ignore plugin actually is just a sampling service. It used `ContextManagerExtendService` extension, just because only sampling service API doesn't provide the operation name.  In this PR, I changed the sampling service API, and move `TraceIgnoreExtendService` to extend it. So conflict goes away.

column3: Increased support for Vertx
column4: - Why submit this pull request? - [x] Improve performance  ___ ### New feature or improvement  I've split the Vert.x Web tests into two scenarios (3.54minus & 3.6plus). In Vert.x 3.6 they introduced the ability to pass the Router directly to the server handler (https://github.com/vert-x3/vertx-web/blob/3.6.0/vertx-web/src/main/java/io/vertx/ext/web/Router.java#L64). To handle this I had to create a new scenario which uses the newer way of setting up the Router. I also added better support for their web-client which is just an extension of the already supported http-client.  You can verify things are correct by comparing `test/plugin/scenarios/vertx-web-3.54minus-scenario/config/expectedData.yaml` to `test/plugin/scenarios/vertx-web-3.6plus-scenario/config/expectedData.yaml`. Even though the Router is setup differently and one uses HttpClient and the other uses WebClient, the `expectedData.yml` files are essentially the same.

column3: Increased Vert.x support
column4: - Why submit this pull request? - [x] Bug fix - [ ] New feature provided - [x] Improve performance  - Related issues  ___ ### Bug fix  Fixes https://github.com/apache/skywalking/issues/3338. @wentjiang had the right idea for the fix but the method chosen to enhance is not present ver. 3.5+. I've chosen another method that also works and is present in all versions.   ___ ### New feature or improvement  I added support for ver. 3.9.1 as well for more complex route handling. The tests I've been using were too simple so I made them more realisitic. The tests I'm using now look like:  - User sends request to `/web-case` - `/web-case` sends a request to `/healthcheck` (ver. 3.5- = sync / ver. 3.6+ = async) - Once response is recieved another request is sent to `/withBodyHandler` (ver. 3.5- = sync / ver. 3.6+ = async) - Before `/withBodyHandler` is called this is processed by Vert.x's internal `BodyHandler` - `BodyHandler` passes request off to `/withBodyHandler` - Once the response is received the original request to `/web-case` is responded to  This results in the segment trace stack: ``` ENTER: /case/web-case      ASYNC SPAN STARTED [1]      LOCAL: VertxWebController$$Lambda$.handle(RoutingContext)           EXIT: /case/healthCheck                ASYNC SPAN STARTED [2]           CLOSE EXIT      CLOSE LOCAL CLOSE ENTER  ENTER: /case/healthCheck      ASYNC SPAN STARTED [3]      LOCAL: VertxWebController$$Lambda$.handle(RoutingContext)            ASYNC SPAN FINISHED [3]      CLOSE LOCAL CLOSE ENTER  ASYNC SPAN FINISHED [2] LOCAL: #/case/healthCheck      EXIT: /case/web-case/withBodyHandler           ASYNC SPAN STARTED [4]      CLOSE EXIT CLOSE LOCAL  ENTER: /case/web-case/withBodyHandler      ASYNC SPAN STARTED [5]      LOCAL: BodyHandlerImpl.handle(RoutingContext)      EXIT LOCAL CLOSE ENTER  LOCAL: VertxWebController$$Lambda$.handle(RoutingContext)      ASYNC SPAN FINISHED [5] CLOSE LOCAL  ASYNC SPAN FINISHED [4] LOCAL: #/vertx-web-3_54minus-scenario/case/web-case/withBodyHandler      ASYNC SPAN FINISHED [1] CLOSE LOCAL ```  If you look at the above the `ENTER: /case/web-case/withBodyHandler` is called on a separate context than `LOCAL: VertxWebController$$Lambda$.handle(RoutingContext)`. This is because of the added `BodyHandlerImpl.handle(RoutingContext)`. This would occur with any additional handlers before the user-code handler. With the added solution you can add additional handlers (e.g. `CorsHandler`) and it'll still result in the spans being created correctly: ![trace-list](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3278877/83239063-591ef480-a1a8-11ea-9afb-65a37c5d7c0e.png)  Apologies for the constant changes. I believe this PR to offer the most thorough support and I wanted to make sure to get better Vert.x support in SkyWalking 8.0.0. When I saw the previous PR couldn't support 3.9.1, I rushed it through because I saw there were bigger changes that I needed to make and I wasn't sure how quickly I could make them.

column3: Better Vert.x endpoint names
column4: - Why submit this pull request? - [ ] Bug fix - [ ] New feature provided - [X] Improve performance  ___ ### New feature or improvement  PR contains two changes. The first is to include the HTTP request method in the endpoint name. A GET endpoint will now have an endpoint like `{GET}/orders`, instead of `/orders`. This follows the same style used in the Spring MVC plugin.  The second change is to implement endpoint name grouping so endpoints like `/order/1` and `/order/2` will have an endpoint name `/order/:id` instead of creating a new endpoint for each unique URL.  Combine those two changes and you get `{POST}/order/:id`, which I believe correctly reflects what an endpoint is expected to be.

column3: Include request method type in rest mapping annotations
column4: - Why submit this pull request? - [ ] Bug fix - [ ] New feature provided - [X] Improve performance  - Related issues slightly related to: https://github.com/apache/skywalking/pull/5084 ___ ### New feature or improvement  Using the `@RequestMapping` will result in an endpoint being saved like `{GET}/users` instead of `/users`. However, using the `@GetMapping` will result in `/users`. This PR will also result in the REST mapping annotations to work like the `@RequestMapping` annotation.  Also, spelling fix.

column3: Customize enhance plugin extensions
column4: - Why do you submit this issue? - [x] Question or discussion  ___ ### Question  I would like to extend the `customize-enhance-plugin` and I would like to know if these changes are of any interest to anyone.  ### Ability to wildcard methods  Instead of choosing every method, it would be nice to be able to say all the methods in a certain class are of interest, like so: ```xml                                     arg[0]             arg[1]             arg[3].[0]             arg[2].['k1']             arg[4].[1]             arg[4].[2]                ```  Here I've said that every static method in `TestService1` should be traced but that the specific method `staticMethod(java.lang.String,int.class,java.util.Map,java.util.List,[Ljava.lang.Object;)` should also be traced with additional data.  Given that getter/setter methods would also be picked up with this approach I would also propose that this wildcard approach by default does not pick those up unless specified via `includeSetters="true"`/`includeGetters="true"`.  ### Ability to wildcard classes  Just like the wildcarding methods, I think it would be beneficial to say that all the classes in a certain package (or sub-packages) are of interest to tracing. Example: ```xml                                     arg[0]             arg[1]             arg[3].[0]             arg[2].['k1']             arg[4].[1]             arg[4].[2]                ```  Here I've said any classes in `test.org.apache.skywalking.apm.testcase.customize.service` and sub-packages should be traced. In those classes all the static methods should be traced (except getter/setter methods) and that any method in any class within those that match the signature `staticMethod(java.lang.String,int.class,java.util.Map,java.util.List,[Ljava.lang.Object;)` should also be traced but with additional settings applied.  ### Ability to choose span type  Instead of just creating local span types I think it would also be beneficial if the span type could be chosen via this plugin. This will increase the ability to programmatically produce tracing configurations for SkyWalking to use. With my project ([Source++](https://github.com/sourceplusplus/assistant)), my plan is to expose a SkyWalking UI to developers inside their IDE. Instead of creating a plugin for SkyWalking or using `@Trace` they could simply hit a keyboard shortcut and a UI would pop up asking them how they would like to trace it, what type of span it is, and what data should be logged/collected. This would then be used in the creation of `customize_enhance.xml` which would be automatically generated and utilized whenever they launch applications via their IDE.  I can also envision the scenario where a solution like this could be used in the creation of more SkyWalking plugins. It can sometimes be difficult to create a SkyWalking plugin across many versions of frameworks (especially async frameworks). With the ability to programmatically chose what types of spans to create it would be much easier to simply choose a couple of methods and then see what that results in and then choose more/other methods and reboot to see if that fixes thing. They would then have a `customize_enhance.xml` file which would tell them the classes/methods/span types they would need to use to make a physical plugin (via skywalking-plugin.def).  I think it would look something like: ```   ``` This would mean that method(s) with the signature `acceptUserRequest(com.example.RequestData)` should create entry spans and the method(s) with the signature `sendUserResponse(com.example.ResponseData)` should create exit spans.  I understand that this isn't currently enough information to correctly add the necessary `ContextCarrier` to those methods but `customize-enhance-plugin` already has a mechanism for logging/tagging user data (e.g. `arg[4].[2]`), so my thought was that there would need to be a way to do that to inject and extract the `ContextCarrier`. I haven't thought too much about this yet so I would appreciate any input.  ----  I've already implemented the ability to wildcard methods, classes, and packages but I'm curious if any of these features (included the ability to specify span type) are something that SkyWalking would like. If not, I'll implement these features as an internal custom plugin.

column3: Using Hugo to refactor Apache SkyWalking's website
column4: - Why do you submit this issue? - [ ] Question or discussion - [ ] Bug - [x] Requirement - [ ] Feature or performance improvement  I propose using [Hugo](https://gohugo.io) to refactor SkyWalking's site, the current site is not user friendly in terms of content organization, and more importantly, the documentation is not put together with the site, you need to jump to GitHub to read the documentation.  I created a prototype of the new website using Hugo, as shown below.  ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3328185/93853795-206ed200-fce7-11ea-8445-e6fefc74403b.png)  Sections can also be added and customized on the home page. The menu can also be modified. The entire website will be rebuilt in two phases: - the  first phase migrating the current website to Hugo - the second phase migrating the documentation to Hugo  Hopefully someone will come along and work with me to refactor the site and make the experience of contributing to SkyWalking and browsing the website more friendly.

column3: Optimize L1 and L2 aggregation.
column4: - L1 Aggregation. Use **MergableBufferedData** to replace **ReadWriteSafeCache**. This could avoid the lock for every time aggregation of L1. - L2 Aggregation. Support **batch mode** in the **MergableBufferedData**, also reduce the lock and lock race for the aggregation of L2. - Remove the ** endOfBatch** from the ** StreamData**. With the batch mode supported in the workers, we don't need that. We take advantage of DataCarrier batch consuming feature.

column3: suggest K8S heml esinit job change CronJob
column4: - [ ] Feature or performance improvement Now esinit is in the form of job and is only executed once against Skywalking Heml, the ALARM_Record in ES will not if there is no data that day The ALARM_Record will continue to be verified by the OAP, causing the POD to fail to start and get stuck in:  table: alarm_record does not exist. OAP is running in 'no-init' mode, waiting，instead of CronJo The ALARM_Record can be rebuilt periodically to handle this, and the CronJo can be executed manually at any time to see if the scheme is viable. Attached is the YAML file of CronJo I am using:  apiVersion: batch/v1beta1 kind: CronJob metadata:   labels:     app: skywalking     chart: skywalking-2.0.0     component: mysw-v2-skywalking-job     heritage: Helm     release: mysw-v2   name: mysw-v2-es-init-cj   namespace: skywalking spec:   schedule: "0 1 * * *"   jobTemplate:     spec:       template:         metadata: {}         spec:           containers:             - env:                 - name: JAVA_OPTS                   value: -Xmx2g -Xms2g -Dmode=init                 - name: SW_STORAGE                   value: elasticsearch7                 - name: SW_STORAGE_ES_CLUSTER_NODES                   value: XXXXX:9200               image: apache/skywalking-oap-server:7.0.0-es7               imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent               name: skywalking-oap               resources: {}               terminationMessagePath: /dev/termination-log               terminationMessagePolicy: File           restartPolicy: Never           schedulerName: default-scheduler           securityContext: {}           terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 30   ### Requirement or improvement - Please describe about your requirements or improvement suggestions.

column3: Implement Extension Header Item in java agent
column4: ### Extension Header Item Extension header item is designed for the advanced features. It provides the interaction capabilities between the agents deployed in upstream and downstream services. * Header Name: `sw8-x` * Header Value: Split by `-`. The fields are extendable.  #### Values The current value includes fields. 1. Tracing Mode. empty, 0 or 1. empty or 0 is default. 1 represents all spans generated in this context should skip analysis, `spanObject#skipAnalysis=true`. This context should be propagated to upstream in the default, unless it is changed in the  tracing process.  Link, https://github.com/apache/skywalking/blob/master/docs/en/protocols/Skywalking-Cross-Process-Propagation-Headers-Protocol-v3.md#extension-header-item  @arugal Once this implements in the Java and go2sky, we should release a new version and enhance the MOSN filter again.  If you have any question about this use case, we could discuss on the bi-weekly meeting directly.

column3: spring gateway pathvariable URL having Parsing problem!!!
column4: ### Bug - Which version of SkyWalking, OS and JRE?   SkyWalking:8.0.1 JDK8  - Which company or project?   Skywalking2.1.5.RELEASE  - What happen?   When accessing /**/{pathvariable} type URL through the gateway。 the endointname style /**/1,/**/2 and many more.  ![Screenshot_5](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3897037/87908412-ea1f9700-ca98-11ea-9cc7-82eaf46c9dd9.png)  ___ ### Requirement or improvement My expected result is that the number variable fragment will be replaced with *。 For example, /user/1,/user/2 will eventually be converted to /user/*. Can you tell me that it is okay to modify that module, or other solutions。

column3: Support percentile function in the meter system.
column4: ## Percentile Function Read [percentile in WIKI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percentile). Unlike in the OAL, we provide 50/75/90/95/99 in default, in the meter system function, percentile function accepts several ranks, which should be in the (0, 100) range.  ## API Usage ```java meterSystem.create(     "test_percentile_metrics", "percentile", ScopeType.SERVICE,     PercentileFunction.PercentileArgument.class );  // Percentile Example final AcceptableValue testPercentileMetrics = service.buildMetrics(     "test_percentile_metrics", PercentileFunction.PercentileArgument.class); testPercentileMetrics.setTimeBucket(TimeBucket.getMinuteTimeBucket(System.currentTimeMillis())); testPercentileMetrics.accept(     MeterEntity.newService("service-test"),     new PercentileFunction.PercentileArgument(         new BucketedValues(             // Buckets             new int[] {                 0,                 51,                 100,                 250             },             // Values             new long[] {                 10,                 20,                 30,                 40             }         ),         // Ranks         new int[] {             50,             90         }     ) ); service.doStreamingCalculation(testPercentileMetrics);                    ```  ## Constraint Condition 1. The buckets and percentile ranks should be consistent for every metrics name. Otherwise, data will be abandoned.   ## GraphQL query ```graphql {   readLabeledMetricsValues(condition : {     name: "test_percentile_metrics",     entity: {       scope: Service,       serviceName: "service-test",       normal: true,     }   },    labels: ["50", "90", "no-labled"]   duration: {step:MINUTE, start: "2020-04-28 1100", end: "2020-04-28 1105"}   ) {     label,     values {       values {         id,         value       }     }   } } ```  ```graphql {   "data": {     "readLabeledMetricsValues": [       {         # Even label doesn't exist in the declaration stage, no error happens. column3: Support histogram function in Meter system.
column4: ## Histogram Function Histogram includes data range buckets and the amount matched/grouped in the buckets. This is for original histogram graph visualization  ## API Usage ```java final MeterSystem service = getManager().find(CoreModule.NAME).provider().getService(MeterSystem.class); // Histogram Example final AcceptableValue histogramMetrics = service.buildMetrics(                         "test_histogram_metrics", BucketedValues.class);  value.setTimeBucket(TimeBucket.getMinuteTimeBucket(System.currentTimeMillis())); histogramMetrics.accept(servEntity, new BucketedValues(                         new long[] {                             0,                             50,                             100,                             250                         },                         new long[] {                             0,                             4,                             10,                             10                         }                     )); service.doStreamingCalculation(histogramMetrics); ```  ## Constraint Condition The time bucket should be set completely at the first place and immutable. Once it is changed,  1. If in the `AcceptableValue` level, `IllegalArgumentException` raised for blocking further calculation. 1. If in the internal `combine` level, such as memory-db combine, warning logs show up, and ignore the combine operation.   Don't change the bucket in any case. If the bucket is really changed, the data will be saved in next time bucket, such as next minute/hour/day based on the precision.  ___ NOTICE, Percentile/Quantiles function will be provided in a similar idea of the `histogram` function,  buckets and ranks should not be changed once they are set.

column3: Group Parameterized Endpoints
column4: # Group Parameterized Endpoints In most cases, the endpoint should be detected automatically through the language agents, service mesh observability solution, or configuration of the meter system.  There are some special cases, especially when people use REST style URI, the application codes put the parameter in the endpoint name, such as putting order id in the URI, like `/prod/ORDER123` and `/prod/ORDER123`. But logically, people expect they could have an endpoint name like `prod/{order-id}`. This is the feature of parameterized endpoint grouping designed for.  Current, user could set up grouping rules through the static YAML file, named `endpoint_name_grouping.yml`, or use Dynamic Configuration to initial and update the endpoint grouping rule.  ## Configuration Format No matter in static local file or dynamic configuration value, they are sharing the same YAML format.  ```yaml grouping:   # Endpoint of the service would follow the following rules   - service-name: serviceA     rules:       # Logic name when the regex expression matched.       - endpoint-name: /prod/{id}         regex: \/prod\/.+ ```
